  "prompt": "Who invented the English alphabet?",
  "response": "The English alphabet as we know it today is derived from the Latin alphabet, which was used by the Romans. The Latin alphabet itself was adapted from the Greek alphabet, and the Greek alphabet was influenced by the Phoenician alphabet. The English alphabet went through a series of transformations over centuries, influenced by various peoples and languages.\n\nThe Romans brought the Latin alphabet to Britain when they invaded, but many of the letters used in Old English were borrowed from the runic alphabets used by the Anglo-Saxons. Over time, as England was Christianized, the Latin script became more prevalent, and additional letters were added or modified to accommodate English sounds. There wasn't a single \"inventor\" of the English alphabet; rather, it evolved over time through cultural exchanges and adaptations.",
